{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = Cradle Tales of Hinduism | image = File:Cradle Tales of Hinduism title page.jpg | caption = Title page | author = [[Sister Nivedita]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | subject = | genre = | publisher = Longmans | publisher2 = | pub_date = | english_pub_date = 1907 | media_type = | pages = 332 pages (paperback) | awards = | isbn = 81-85301-93-X | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Cradle Tales of Hinduism''''' (1907) is a collection of stories by [[Sister Nivedita]].<ref name="Publication2002">{{cite book|author=Cosmo Publication|title=Eminent Orientalist: Indian, American and European|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IN2Ev-ZYtD0C&pg=PA211|accessdate=October 12, 2012|date=May 1, 2002|publisher=Cosmo Publications|isbn=978-81-7755-027-6|pages=211–}}</ref> It is an introduction to [[Hindu mythology]]; the stories come from the [[Mahabharata]], the [[Ramayana]] and other Hindu sources and are presented as they were told in Indian nurseries.<ref>Author's Preface to ''Cradle Tales of Hinduism'': The book is described as "a collection of genuine Indian nursery-tales".</ref>
==Background== Nivedita travelled to India in 1898. [[Josephine MacLeod]], a friend and devotee of [[Swami Vivekananda]] asked him how best she could help him and got the reply to "Love India". Nivedita wanted to interpret Indian culture to the Western world and so wrote this book.<ref name="Banhatti1995">{{cite book|author=G. S Banhatti|title=Life And Philosophy Of Swami Vivekananda|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jK5862eV7_EC&pg=PA37|accessdate=October 12, 2012|date=January 1, 1995|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|isbn=978-81-7156-291-6|pages=37–}}</ref>
