This is a '''list of geographic centers''' of each [[U.S. state]]. Note that the [[Geographic center of the United States|geographic center]] of the entire U.S. is northeast of [[Belle Fourche, South Dakota|Belle Fourche]] in [[Butte County, South Dakota]] {{coord|44|58|N|103|46|W|region:US-SD_type:landmark|display=inline}}, while that of the [[Geographic Center of the Contiguous United States|contiguous 48]] is near [[Lebanon, Kansas|Lebanon]] in [[Smith County, Kansas]] {{coord|39|50|N|98|35|W|region:US-KS_type:landmark|name=Geographic Center of the Contiguous United States}}. The geographic center of North America lies near [[Rugby, North Dakota]] {{coord|48|22|2|N|99|59|46|W|region:US-ND_type:city|display=inline}}, though this designation has no official status.
==Centers of the states and Washington, DC== The list given below has been only slightly modified since it was first produced by the U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) in the early 1920s.<ref> Douglas, E.M. 1923. Boundaries, Areas, Geographic Centers, and Altitudes of the United States and Several States. Bulletin 689. U.S. Geological Survey, Washington, DC. </ref> At that time, the center for a state was found by suspending a cardboard cutout of the state by a string, and then drawing a vertical line from the suspension point. After rotating the cutout 90 degrees and drawing another vertical line from the new suspension point, the intersection of the two vertical lines was used as the geographic center.<ref> Adams, Oscar, S. 1932. Geographical Centers. The Military Engineer 24, 138: 586-587.</ref> The result is dependent upon the type of projection used.
